ica101-103\"/>\n|16 March 1361<ref name=\"Britannica101-103\"/>\n|Kipchak Turk\n|Second reign. He was killed by Emir [[Yalbugha al-Umari]].<ref name=\"Britannica101-103\"/>\n|[[File:Copper fals of an-Nasir Hasan.jpg|100x100px]]\n|- bgcolor=\"#b2dfdf\"\n|24th\n|Al-Malik al-Mansur\n|[[Al-Mansur Muhammad, Sultan of Egypt|Salah ad-Din Muhammad]]\n|17 March 1361<ref name=\"Britannica101-103\"/>\n|29 May 1363<ref name=\"Britannica101-103\"/>\n|Kipchak Turk\n|Son of Hajji. Real power was held by Emir Yalbugha al-Umari, who toppled him.<ref name=\"Britannica101-103\"/>\n|[[File:Dinar LACMA M.2006.143.8 (1 of 2).jpg|100x100px]]\n|- bgcolor=\"#b2dfdf\"\n|25th\n|Al-Malik al-Ashraf\n|[[Al-Ashraf Sha'ban|Zayn ad-Din Sha'ban]] (Sha'ban II)\n|29 May 1363<ref name=\"Britannica101-103\"/>\n|15 March 1377<ref name=\"Britannica101-103\"/>\n|Kipchak Turk\n|Son of al-Amjad Husayn (d. 21 January 1363), the last surviving son of an-Nasir Muhammad who never reigned,<ref>Holt, eds. Vermeulen and De Smet, p. 319.</ref> and Khawand Baraka.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Al-Harithy|first1=Howayda|editor1-last=Sonbol|editor1-first=Amira El Azhary|title=Beyond The Exotic: Women's Histories In Islamic Societies|date=2005|publisher=Syracuse University Press|isbn=9780815630555|page=332|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uUe8tBUvwE4C&pg=PA332|chapter=Female Patronage of Mamluk Architecture in Cairo}}</ref>\n|[[File:Mamluk Shaban II copper fals Hama.jpg|100x100px]]\n|- bgcolor=\"#b2dfdf\"\n|26th\n|Al-Malik al-Mansur\n|[[Al-Mansur Ali II, Sultan of Egypt|Ala'a ad-Din Ali]]\n|15 March 1377<ref name=\"Britannica101-103\"/>\n|19 May 1381<ref name=\"Britannica101-103\"/>\n|Kipchak Turk\n|Son of Sha'ban II. Was an infant during his accession, and real power was initially held by emirs Ibek and Qartay until the latter was ousted by the former. Ibek was later killed and power passed to [[Barquq]], a former ''mamluk'' of Yalbugha an-Nasiri.\n|[[File:M56 fals Bahrites 1ar85 (8594902625).jpg|100x100px]]\n|- bgcolor=\