monarchs]]\n[[Category:Sultans of the Mamluk Sultanate (Cairo)| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of rulers of Egypt|Mamluk Sultans]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n[[File:Citadel of Salah el deen al ayoubi 03.JPG|thumb|right|The [[Cairo Citadel]], the seat of power of the Mamluk sultans]]\nThe following is a '''list of Mamluk sultans'''. The [[Mamluk Sultanate (Cairo)|Mamluk Sultanate]] was founded in 1250 by ''[[mamluk]]s'' of the [[Ayyubid dynasty|Ayyubid]] sultan [[as-Salih Ayyub]] and it succeeded the Ayyubid state. It was based in [[Cairo]] and for much of its history, the territory of the sultanate spanned Egypt, [[Syria (region)|Syria]] and parts of [[Anatolia]], [[Upper Mesopotamia]] and the [[Hejaz]]. The sultanate ended with the advent of the [[Ottoman Empire]] in 1517.\n\nThere were a total of 47 sultans, although Sultan [[an-Nasir Muhammad]] reigned three times, and sultans [[an-Nasir Hasan]], Salah ad-Din Hajji, [[Barquq]] and [[an-Nasir Faraj]] each reigned twice. The Mamluk period is generally divided into two periods, the [[Bahri dynasty|Bahri]] and [[Burji dynasty|Burji]] periods. The Bahri sultans were predominantly of [[Turkic people|Turkic]] origins, while the Burji sultans were predominantly ethnic [[Circassians]]. While the first three Mamluk sultans, [[Aybak]], his son [[al-Mansur Ali]], and [[Qutuz]], are generally considered part of the Bahri dynasty, they were not part of the Bahriyya ''mamluk'' regiment and opposed the political interests of the Bahriyya.<ref name=\"Northrup6970\">Northrup 1998, pp. 69\u201370.</ref> The first sultan to come from the Bahriyya's ranks was [[Baibars|Baybars]].<ref name=\"Northrup6970\"/> The Burji ''mamluks'' usurped the throne in 1382 with the accession of Sultan Barquq. The 34th sultan, [[Al-Musta'in (Cairo)|al-Musta'in Billah]], was also the [[Abbasid caliph]] and was installed in power by the Burji emirs as a figurehead.<ref name=\"Britannica101-103\"/>\n\n==List of sultans==\n{{clear}}\n{| class=\"nowraplinks\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"3\" rules=\"all\" style=\"background:#fbfbfb; border-style: solid; border-width: 1px; font-size:90%; empty-cells:show; border-collapse:collapse\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"11\" |\n{{legend2|#e5e5e5|Salihi Mamluks|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n{{legend2|#b2dfdf|[[Bahri dynasty]]|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n{{legend2|#fffab4|[[Burji dynasty]]|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#f6e6ae;\"\n! Number !! Royal title !! Name !! Reign start !! Reign end !! Ethnicity !! Background notes !! Coinage\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"#e5e5e5\"\n|1st\n|Al-Malik al-Mu'izz\n|[[Aybak|Izz ad-Din Aybak]]\n|31 July 1250<ref name=\"Northrup69\">Northrup 1998, p. 69.</ref>\n|10 April 1257<ref>Northrup 1998, p. 70.</ref>\n|[[Turkmens|Turkmen]]\n|Middle-ranking ''mamluk'' of [[Ayyubid dynasty|Ayyubid]] sultan [[as-Salih Ayyub]]. Married the latter's widow, [[Shajar al-Durr|Shajar ad-Durr]], who became sultan on 2 May 1250 until she abdicated in favor of Aybak.<ref name=\"Northrup69\"/>\n|[[File:Silver dirham of Aybak.jpg|100x100px]]\n|- bgcolor=\"#e5e5e5\"\n|2nd\n|Al-Malik al-Mansur\n|[[al-Mansur Ali|Nur ad-Din Ali]]\n|15 April 1257<ref name=\"Stewart86\">{{cite book|last1=Stewart|first1=John|title=African States and Rulers|date=2006|publisher=McFarland & Company|isbn=9780786425624|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I7UUAQAAIAAJ&dq=al-Mansur+Ali+16+April+1257&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%2215+April+1257%22|page=86}}</ref>\n|November 1259<ref name=\"Stewart86\"/>\n|[[Turkmens|Turkmen]]\n|Son of Aybak.\n|[[File:Gold dinar of al-Mansur Nur ad-Din Ali.jpg|100x100px]]\n|- bgcolor=\"#e5e5e5\"\n|3rd\n|Al-Malik al-Muzaffar\n|[[Qutuz|Sayf ad-Din Qutuz]]\n|November 1259<ref name=\"Stewart86\"/>\n|24 October 1260<ref name=\"Stewart86\"/>\n|[[Khwarazmian dynasty|Khwarazmian Turk]]<ref name=\"Hathaway50-52\">{{cite book|last1=Hathaway|first1=Jane|title=Tale of Two Factions, A: Myth, Memory, and Identity in Ottoman Egypt and Yemen|date=2003|publisher=State University of New York Press|isbn=9780791486108|pages=50\u201352|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L-lPC7DgepEC&pg=PA51}}</ref>\n|A ''mamluk'' of Aybak and head of Aybak's ''mamluk'' faction, the Mu'izziya,<ref name=\"NorthrupPetry250\">Northrup, ed. Petry 1998, p. 250.</ref> Aybak's chief deputy, and strongman of Ali's sultanate.<ref name=\"Northrup71\">Northrup 1998, p. 71.</ref>\n|[[File:Qutuz gold dinar obverse.jpg|100x100px]]\n|- bgcolor=\"#b2dfdf\"\n|4th\n|Al-Malik az-Zahir\n|[[Baibars|Rukn ad-Din Baybars]]\n|24 October 1260<ref name=\"Stewart86\"/>\n|1 July 1277<ref name=\"Stewart86\"/>\n|Kipchak Turk\n|Bahri ''mamluk'' and founder of the [[Bahri dynasty]].<ref name=\"NorthrupPetry250\"/>\n|[[File:Egitto, califfo al baybars, dinar mamelucco, 1260-1277.JPG|100x100px]]\n|- bgcolor=\"#b2dfdf\"\n|5th\n|Al-Malik as-Sa'id\n|[[Al-Said Barakah|Nasir ad-Din Barakah]]\n|3 July 1277<ref name=\"Stewart86\"/>\n|August 1279<ref name=\"Stewart86\"/>\n|Kipchak Turk\n|Son of Baybars and his wife, who was the daughter of Husam ad-Din Baraka Khan, a Khwarazmian warrior chief, after whom Barakah was named.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Thorau|first1=Peter|title=The Lion of Egypt: Sultan Baybars I and the Near East in the Thirteenth Century|date=1992|publisher=Longman|isbn=9780582068230|page=261|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kRAOAQAAMAAJ&dq=Khwarazmian+Baybars+son&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22the+chief+of+that+band+of+Khwarazmian%22}}</ref><ref name=\"Hathaway50-52\"/><ref>Holt 2004, p. 99.</ref>\n|[[File:Barakah coin.jpg|100x100px]]\n|- bgcolor=\"#b2dfdf\"\n|6th\n|Al-Malik al-Adil\n|[[Solamish|Badr ad-Din Salamish]]\n|August 1279<ref name=\"Stewart86\"/>\n|November 1279<ref name=\"Stewart86\"/>\n|Kipchak Turk\n|Son of Baybars.\n|\n|- bgcolor=\"#b2dfdf\"\n|7th\n|Al-Malik al-Mansur\n|[[Qalawun|Sayf ad-Din Qalawun]]\n|November 1279<ref name=\"Stewart86\"/>\n|10 November 1290<ref name=\"Stewart86\"/>\n|Kipchak Turk{{sfn|Yosef|2012b|p=394}}\n|Bahri ''mamluk'' and Baybars